<!-- ═══════════ OVERVIEW ═══════════ -->
<section id="overview">
  <div class="section-label">Overview</div>
  <h2>What is ETDM?</h2>
  <p class="lead">
    Classical distributed algorithms suffer severe performance degradation as packet loss 
    increases — especially on high-diameter topologies like Rings. ETDM augments these 
    algorithms with dynamically discovered <em>twin shortcuts</em> that bridge distant 
    regions of the network, reducing effective diameter and accelerating information propagation.
  </p>

  <div class="cards">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="icon">🔍</div>
      <h3>Runtime Twin Discovery</h3>
      <p>No oracle, no prior knowledge. Twins are discovered at runtime through EWMA scoring 
         and a three-way handshake protocol over the same lossy channel.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="icon">📡</div>
      <h3>Lossy Channel Model</h3>
      <p>Deterministic BLAKE2b-based loss oracle ensures reproducibility. Per-link loss 
         rates with twin links enjoying lower loss ($q_{\text{twin}} \ll q_{\text{base}}$).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="icon">⚡</div>
      <h3>Shortcut-Based Acceleration</h3>
      <p>Discovered twins create non-neighbor shortcuts, reducing Ring diameter from 
         $\lfloor n/2 \rfloor$ to ~$\lfloor n/4 \rfloor$ and diffusion time from $O(n^2)$ to $O(n)$.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="icon">🧪</div>
      <h3>Fair Experimental Framework</h3>
      <p>Both classical and ETDM algorithms run on the same network instance, same loss oracle, 
         same seed — ensuring a rigorous, apples-to-apples comparison.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

